       n = n // 2        i = 3        max_i = int(n  0.5) + 1        while i <= max_i and n > 1:            while n % i == 0:                factors[i] = factors.get(i, 0) + 1                n = n // i                max_i = int(n  0.5) + 1            i += 2        if n > 1:            factors[n] = 1        return factors        def generate_divisors(factors):        divisors = [1]        for prime, exp in factors.items():            new_divisors = []            for d in divisors:                current = d                for e in range(exp + 1):                    new_divisors.append(current)                    current *= prime            divisors = new_divisors        return divisors        phi = p - 1    factors = factorize(phi)    divisors = generate_divisors(factors)    divisors = sorted(divisors)        order = None    for d in divisors:        if pow(10, d, p) == 1:            order = d            break        if order % 2 == 0:        altsum_n = order // 2        return f\\"{altsum_n}-altsum\\"    else:        return f\\"{order}-sum\\"\`\`\` Explanation1. Special Cases Handling: The primes 2 and 5 are handled directly as their divisibility rules are based on the last digit.2. Factorization: The function \`factorize\` decomposes (p-1) into its prime factors, which helps in generating all possible divisors efficiently.3. Divisors Generation: Using the prime factors, the function \`generate_divisors\` generates all divisors of (p-1) to check the multiplicative order.4. Multiplicative Order Calculation: By iterating through sorted divisors, the smallest divisor \`d\` where (10^d equiv 1 mod p) is found, which gives the multiplicative order.5. Alternating Sum Check: If the multiplicative order is even, the half-order is checked for the alternating sum method, ensuring the smallest \`n\` is chosen.This approach efficiently combines number theory and modular arithmetic to determine the optimal divisibility testing method for any given prime number."},{"problem":"# 